==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spaniel
<hw>Span"iel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>espagneul</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧pagneul</ets>, <ets>espagnol</ets>
Spanish, Sp. <ets>espa⟦ntil⟧nol</ets>, fr. <ets>Espa⟦ntil⟧a</ets> Spain,
from L. <ets>Hispania</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>One of a breed of small dogs having long and thick hair and large
drooping ears. The legs are usually strongly feathered, and the tail
bushy. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Clumber</er>, and
<er>Cocker</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ There are several varieties of spaniels, some of which,
known as <xex>field spaniels</xex>, are used in hunting; others are used
for toy or pet dogs, as the Blenheim spaniel, and the King Charles
spaniel (see under <er>Blenheim</er>). Of the field spaniels, the larger
kinds are called <xex>springers</xex>, and to these belong the Sussex,
Norfolk, and Clumber spaniels (see <er>Clumber</er>). The smaller field
spaniels, used in hunting woodcock, are called <xex>cocker
spaniels</xex> (see Cocker). Field spaniels are remarkable for their
activity and intelligence.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As a <qex>spaniel</qex> she will on him leap.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cringing, fawning person.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spaniel</ent>⟦br⟧

